2 Introduction

The NZ GREEN Grid household electricity demand study recruited a sample of c 25 households in each of two regions of New Zealand (Stephenson et al. 2017). The first sample was recruited in early 2014 and the second in early 2015. Research data includes:

  • 1 minute electricity power (W) data was collected for each dwelling circuit using GridSpy monitors on each power circuit (and the incoming power). The power values represent mean(W) over the minute preceeding the observation timestamp;
  • Dwelling & appliance surveys;
  • Occupant time-use diaries (focused on energy use).

NB: Version 1 of the data package does not include the time-use diaries.

This report provides summary analysis of one circuit type (Heat Pump) across all households as an example.

Note that:

  • r_datetime is the correct dateTime of each observation in UTC and will have loaded as your local timezone. If you are conducting this analysis outside NZ then you will get strange results until you use lubridate to tell R to use tz = “Pacific/Auckland” with this variable;
  • there can be 0 Wh observations.

4 Plot seasonal mean power profiles

This section plots overall mean power (W) per minute by season and number of children aged 0-12 as an illustration of how to link the Grid Spy and household data. We will go through the steps with commentary and showing the code…

First we create a Southern Hemisphere season variable. Luckily we have a function to do this in the GREENGridData package. We print a check table to ensure we are all happy with the coding of season.

gsDT <- GREENGridData::addNZSeason(gsDT)
table(lubridate::month(gsDT$r_dateTime, label = TRUE), gsDT$season)

Table 4.1 the number of households who have different number sof children aged 0-12 so we know how many households make up each line on the chart. This table includes households where we do not know the number of children (NA) but we do have electricity demand data.

Now we link (join) the Grid Spy and household data.tables and aggregate (summarise) by season and number of children aged 0-12. You can do this using data.table’s on the fly join but we have found pre-joining of the columns you want to be much faster. We have wrapped both methods inside system.time() calls for comparison.

You can probably also do this in dplyr etc but we haven’t tried.

print("data.table join on the fly (version 1 - slow):")
## [1] "data.table join on the fly (version 1 - slow):"
system.time(plotDT <- gsDT[hhDT][, .(meanW = mean(powerW)), keyby = .(season, obsTime, nChildren0_12)
             ]) # aggregate by season, time and n children aged 0 - 12
##    user  system elapsed 
##  23.788   3.920  29.667
# print("data.table join on the fly (version 2):")
# # appears to be as specified in https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/data.table/vignettes/datatable-faq.html#MergeDiff
# # but fails to find nChildren0_12
# system.time(plotDT <- gsDT[hhDT, .(meanW = mean(powerW)), keyby = .(season, obsTime, nChildren0_12)
#              ]) # aggregate by season, time and n children aged 0 - 12

aggFunc <- function(gsDT, hhDT){
  # do it in stages instead
  keepCols <- c("linkID", "nChildren0_12")
  mergedDT <- gsDT[hhDT[, ..keepCols]]
  dt <- mergedDT[, .(meanW = mean(powerW)), keyby = .(season, obsTime, nChildren0_12)]
  return(dt)
}
print("data.table merge then aggregate:")
## [1] "data.table merge then aggregate:"
system.time(plotDT <- aggFunc(gsDT, hhDT))
##    user  system elapsed 
##   3.909   0.229   4.160

Now use the aggregated data.table to make the plot. Note that as specified this will add a line for nChildren0_12 == NA (household(s).

# set attributes for plot
vLineAlpha <- 0.4
vLineCol <- "#0072B2" # http://www.cookbook-r.com/Graphs/Colors_(ggplot2)/#a-colorblind-friendly-palette
timeBreaks <- c(hms::as.hms("04:00:00"), 
                hms::as.hms("08:00:00"),
                hms::as.hms("12:00:00"),
                hms::as.hms("16:00:00"),
                hms::as.hms("20:00:00"),
                hms::as.hms("24:00:00")
)

myPlot <- ggplot2::ggplot(plotDT, aes(x = obsTime, y = meanW/1000, colour = as.factor(nChildren0_12))) +
  geom_line() + 
  facet_grid(season  ~ .) + 
  theme(strip.text.y = element_text(angle = 0, vjust = 0.5, hjust = 0.5)) + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust = 0.5)) + 
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") + 
  theme(legend.title=element_blank()) + 
  labs(title = paste0("Seasonal mean power demand profiles by n children aged 0-12: ", params$circuit),
       y = "Mean kW", 
       caption = paste0("GREENGrid Grid Spy household electricity demand data",
                        "\n", min(gsDT$r_dateTime), 
                        " to ", max(gsDT$r_dateTime),
                        "\nobsTime = Pacific/Auckland"))

myPlot + 
  scale_x_time(breaks = timeBreaks) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = timeBreaks, alpha = vLineAlpha, colour = vLineCol)
## Warning: Removed 4 rows containing missing values (geom_path).
